Data and data management in R: A primer

In this section of the lab we are going to use data from the General Social Survey made available in R throught the gssr package.

Basics of R, matrices and Data

For this discussion I have included Charlie Geyers R notes from his introduction to Computational Statistics course below. These notes are excellent and we will review them in course briefly.

  • R Basics
  • Arrays
  • Data Basics

## We will have to write our own statistical mode function!
stat_mode<-function(x){
  tab<-as.data.frame(table(x))
  index<-which.max(tab$Freq)
  as.numeric(as.character(tab[index,1]))
}

##stat mode
stat_mode(age[[1]])
[1] 34
## sum with na's removed
sum(age[[1]],na.rm=TRUE)
[1] 114642

Statistical Tests in R

permutation test

  • Permutation Test Notes form our Friends in Bio-Stats

To estimate the sampling distribution of the test statistic we need many samples generated under the strong null hypothesis.

If the null hypothesis is true, changing the exposure would have no effect on the outcome. By randomly shuffling the exposures we can make up as many data sets as we like.

If the null hypothesis is true the shuffled data sets should look like the real data, otherwise they should look different from the real data.

The ranking of the real test statistic among the shuffled test statistics gives a p-value

data

## make up some true data
carrier<-rep(c(0,1), c(100,200))
null.y<-rnorm(300)
alt.y<-rnorm(300, mean=carrier/2)

t-test

t.test(null.y~carrier, var.equal=TRUE)

    Two Sample t-test

data:  null.y by carrier
t = 0.4367, df = 298, p-value = 0.6626
alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
95 percent confidence interval:
 -0.1769742  0.2779167
sample estimates:
mean in group 0 mean in group 1 
     0.04582722     -0.00464404 
t.test(alt.y~carrier, var.equal=TRUE)

    Two Sample t-test

data:  alt.y by carrier
t = -4.2322, df = 298, p-value = 3.085e-05
alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
95 percent confidence interval:
 -0.7388232 -0.2698087
sample estimates:
mean in group 0 mean in group 1 
   -0.006895269     0.497420697

mean test

null.diff<-mean(null.y[carrier==1])-mean(null.y[carrier==0])
alt.diff<-mean(alt.y[carrier==1])-mean(alt.y[carrier==0])
one.test <- function(x,y) {
xstar<-sample(x)
mean(y[xstar==1])-mean(y[xstar==0])
}
many.truenull <- replicate(1000, one.test(carrier, null.y))
many.falsenull <- replicate(1000, one.test(carrier, alt.y))
